verifying onLoad call order in a unit test without needing real module loading.","test_description":"Create mock plugins A and B where A's manifest declares a dependency on B. Instrument both plugins' onLoad hooks with spies (e.g., Mock or Jest mock functions). Invoke the loader and assert that B's onLoad.mock.calls[0] occurs before A's onLoad.mock.calls[0] by examining call timestamps or assertion order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit-level probability (0.60) exceeds Integration (0.40). The dependency resolution logic itself is testable at unit level, though integration testing with real manifest parsing would provide robustness against manifest schema errors.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.6,"Integration":0.4,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Cycle detection is a pure algorithmic problem with no runtime or infrastructure dependencies. The failure is either: the cycle-detection algorithm misses the cycle, or the prevention logic fails to stop loading. Both are deterministic logical failures testable at unit level with mock plugin data (plugin A depends on B, plugin B depends on A). No I/O, subprocess, or real module loading is needed.","test_description":"Create mock plugins A and B where A's manifest declares dependency on B AND B's manifest declares dependency on A. Call the loader and assert: (1) an error or exception is raised reporting the cycle, (2) neither plugin's require() is called, (3) neither plugin's onLoad() is called, (4) the loader does not return a successful load result.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit-level probability (0.85) strongly exceeds Integration (0.15). This is pure logic with no hidden infrastructure concerns.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.15,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's onLoad hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The behavior explicitly requires that the module is 'imported and executed' before onLoad is invoked. While a unit test mocking require() could verify the call sequence (require before onLoad), it cannot verify that actual module code executes, because the mock does not run real initialization code. The failure—onLoad called when the module is not yet initialized—would only manifest when module-level state or side effects are needed. Integration testing with a real plugin module that has observable side effects (e.g., module-level variable set during import) is necessary to verify that module execution actually happened before onLoad.","test_description":"Create a real plugin module that sets a module-level flag or initializes state during import (e.g., `let initialized = true` at the top of the module, or a file write). The plugin's onLoad hook depends on this state or flag. Load the plugin and assert: (1) the module's side effect (flag, file, or state) was set before onLoad was invoked, (2) onLoad successfully accesses the module state, confirming the module was fully initialized.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration-level probability (0.70) exceeds Unit (0.30). Unit testing with mocks can verify call order but cannot verify that real module code is executed; integration testing with a real module catches the actual failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.7,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The core failure is in error handling logic and dependency-based filtering. The loader must catch the error, mark the plugin as failed, and load only remaining plugins that do not have a dependency on the failed one. This is deterministic logical logic testable at unit level by mocking three plugins (one that fails, one that depends on it, one that does not), triggering the failure, and asserting the loader's state afterward. The logical filtering decision can be verified without real I/O.","test_description":"Create mock plugins: B with an onLoad hook that throws an error, A whose manifest declares a dependency on B, and C that is independent. Mock each onLoad with a spy to track execution. Call the loader and assert: (1) B's error is caught and not allowed to crash the loader, (2) A's onLoad is not called (dependency unsatisfied due to B's failure), (3) C's onLoad is called successfully (no dependency on B). Verify using call counts (A should have 0 calls, C should have 1 call).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit-level probability (0.80) exceeds Integration (0.20). The error handling and filtering logic is testable at unit level, though integration testing with real manifests would provide additional confidence in the filtering behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.2,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13481,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13481},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e347832a-5f2c-4490-9077-633baadf8f7c","uuid":"4c2986c4-a910-4e6c-865d-9dc4f42236af"}
